.TH BIOJOIN 1 "March 2026" "biojoin" "Bioinformatics Tools"

.SH NAME
biojoin \- join genomic or tabular files by keys or genomic coordinates

.SH SYNOPSIS
.B biojoin++
.RI [ OPTIONS ] " FILE1 FILE2"

.SH DESCRIPTION
.B biojoin
is a command-line utility for joining two tabular files based on
user-defined key fields or genomic coordinates.

The program is designed for genomic datasets such as BED, GTF,
and GFF files but also supports generic delimiter-separated tables.

biojoin builds an in-memory dictionary from the first input file and
then scans the second file to find matching keys. Matching rows
can be combined using different relational join strategies.

This design enables efficient lookups for large genomic datasets.

The program is conceptually similar to database joins and tools
such as
.BR join (1)
but optimized for genomic interval formats commonly used in
bioinformatics workflows.

.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-h
Display help information and exit.

.TP
.B \-b
Interpret the first input file as BED format.
The join key will automatically use the columns:
chromosome, start, and end.

.TP
.B \-B
Interpret the second input file as BED format.

.TP
.B \-g
Interpret the first input file as GTF or GFF format.

.TP
.B \-G
Interpret the second input file as GTF or GFF format.

.TP
.BI \-f " FIELDS"
Specify fields from the first file to build the join key.
Fields must be provided as comma-separated column indices
starting from 0.

Example:
.RS
-f 0,1,2
.RE

.TP
.BI \-s " FIELDS"
Specify fields from the second file to build the join key.

.TP
.BI \-d " CHAR"
Field separator used in the first file.
Default is tab.

.TP
.BI \-e " CHAR"
Field separator used in the second file.
Default is tab.

.TP
.BI \-o " CHAR"
Field separator to use in the output.
Default is tab.

.TP
.BI \-j " TYPE"
Join strategy to use.

Valid values:

.RS
INNER
.br
LEFT_INCLUSIVE
.br
LEFT_EXCLUSIVE
.RE

Default:
.B INNER

.SH JOIN MODES
.TP
.B INNER
Only rows with matching keys in both files are printed.

.TP
.B LEFT_INCLUSIVE
All rows from the first file are printed. If a matching key exists in 
the second file, data is merged; otherwise, missing fields are 
indicated with a null value (e.g., a point).

.TP
.B LEFT_EXCLUSIVE
Rows from the first file are printed only when NO matching key 
exists in the second file. This identifies records unique to the 
first sample.


.SH FILE FORMATS
biojoin supports generic tabular text files.

Input files must be plain text where fields are separated by a
single delimiter character.

Lines beginning with the character '#'
are treated as comments and ignored.

Column indices start at 0.

.SS BED FORMAT
BED files typically contain genomic intervals with at least
three columns:

.RS
chromosome
.br
start
.br
end
.RE

Example:

.RS
chr17    7668420    7677451    TP53
.RE

.SS GTF FORMAT
GTF and GFF files contain genomic annotations.
The coordinate system differs slightly from BED, so biojoin
automatically adjusts coordinates when necessary.

.SH ALGORITHM
biojoin builds an in-memory hash table using the first input file.
Keys are constructed by concatenating the selected fields.

The hash table uses an unordered multimap structure so that
multiple rows may share the same key.

The second file is then streamed line-by-line. For each row,
a key is constructed and used to query the dictionary.

Matching rows are returned in constant average lookup time.

.SH PERFORMANCE
Lookup operations rely on a hash table implementation based on
C++ unordered_multimap.

This approach provides:

.RS
O(1) average lookup time
.br
efficient handling of duplicate keys
.br
scalability for large genomic datasets
.RE

Memory usage depends primarily on the size of the first input file.

.SH EXAMPLES
Join two BED files by genomic coordinates:

.RS
biojoin++ -b -B genes.bed annotations.bed
.RE

Perform a left outer join:

.RS
biojoin++ -j LEFT_OUTER -b -B file1.bed file2.bed
.RE

Join using explicit columns:

.RS
biojoin++ -f 0,1 -s 0,1 file1.tsv file2.tsv
.RE

Change output delimiter:

.RS
biojoin++ -o ',' file1.tsv file2.tsv
.RE

.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
0
Successful execution.

.TP
1
Program terminated due to an error such as invalid arguments
or file access failure.

